Yudhisthira’s kingship, is the revelation that neither of the contesting moieties of the royal Hastinapura clan triumphs in the end, for it is the Yadava band of Krsna who achieve real victory. That is, it is the matriline and not the patriline that secures ultimate success: it is the kinship group of Krsna—the heroic figure who was to become the dominant Vaisnava icon of classical India—who benefits most from the terrible Bharata war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aKings and rulers in literature. 0aYudhiṣṭhira (Hindu mythology) 0aYudhiṣṭhira (Hindu mythology). 4aAsian Studies. 4aFolklore. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Indic.2bisacsh1 aNagy, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170822040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501708220423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501708220/original  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles